shire, England","England":"England","Emley, Yorkshire, England":"Emley, Yorkshire, England","Sprotbrough, Yorkshire, England":"Sprotbrough, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William FitzGodric de Sprotborough was born in 1140, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Godric FitzKetelborn, was 37 and his mother, Lady Ella de Warrene, was 36. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Aubrey de Lisours. He died in 1194, in Sprotbrough, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 54, and was buried in Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1140–1194":"1140–1194","1128–1194":"1128–1194","1160–1195":"1160–1195","–1223":"–1223","1103–Male":"1103–Surnud","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1128":"1128","before 1125":"enne 1125","1105":"1105","1103":"1103","1223":"1223","1140":"1140","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1160":"1160","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Hopton, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Emley, Yorkshire, England":"Emley, Yorkshire, England","Sprotbrough, Yorkshire, England":"Sprotbrough, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1140–1194":"1140–1194","1128–1194":"1128–1194","1160–1195":"1160–1195","–1223":"–1223","1103–Male":"1103–Kuollut","1105–Female":"1105–Kuollut","1128":"1128","before 11